The [answer][1] by Oleg is a good one for what you want to do.

There is a little known feature with Jackson called **[Mixins][2]**. They allow you to provide overrides, annotations and any other desired modifications just to specific places in your complex object graph. This means that you can customize specific aspects of the serialization without having to implement a whole new serializer.

    ObjectMapper mapper = new ObjectMapper();
    mapper.addMixInAnnotations(Class1.class, Class1Mixin.class);

    public Class1
    {
       public String name;
       public int id;    
    }

    public abstract Class1Mixin
    {
       // Override &#39;name&#39; to serialize as &#39;fullName&#39;. Leave the id the same.
       @JsonProperty(&quot;fullName&quot;)
       public String name;    
    }

Think of if as being able to overlay annotations on top of little sections of the object graph without polluting your original classes. Super handy for keeping Models clean and using **[Mixins][2]** to specify how to make them Data Transfer Objects(DTO)/Messages.


  [1]: https://stackoverflow.com/a/74539561/231860
  [2]: https://medium.com/@shankar.ganesh.1234/jackson-mixin-a-simple-guide-to-a-powerful-feature-d984341dc9e2

